{{About|the theorem in probability|the theorem in electricity|Bartlett's bisection theorem}}
In [[queueing theory]], '''Bartlett's theorem''' gives the distribution of the number of customers in a given part of a system at a fixed time.

==Theorem==
Suppose that customers arrive according to a non-stationary [[Poisson process]] with rate ''A''(''t''), and that subsequently they move independently  around a system of nodes. Write ''E'' for some particular part of the system and ''p''(''s'',''t'') the probability that a customer who arrives at time ''s'' is in ''E'' at time ''t''. Then the number of customers in ''E'' at time ''t'' has a [[Poisson distribution]] with mean<ref>{{cite book | title = Poisson Processes | page = 49 | first = John | last = Kingman | authorlink = John Kingman | year = 1993 | isbn = 0198536933 | publisher = Oxford University Press }}</ref>
::<math>\mu(t) = \int_{-\infty}^t A(s) p(s,t) \, \mathrm{d}t.</math>

