{{About|the United States Department of Defense computer network||National Institute of Polar Research (Japan)}}

The '''Non-classified Internet Protocol (IP) Router Network'''<ref>[http://www.disa.mil/Network-Services/Enterprise-Connections/Acronyms DISA acronym list]</ref> ('''NIPRNet''') is a private IP network used to exchange unclassified information, including [[sensitive but unclassified|information subject to controls on distribution]],<ref>[http://disa.mil/Services/Network-Services/Data/SBU-IP DISA website, "Sensitive but Unclassified IP Data (formerly known as NIPRNet)"]</ref> among the private network's users. The NIPRNet also provides its users access to the [[Internet]].

NIPRNet is composed of [[Internet Protocol]] [[Router (computing)|routers]] owned by the [[United States Department of Defense]] (DOD). It was created in the 1980s and managed by the [[Defense Information Systems Agency]] (DISA) to supersede the earlier [[MILNET]].<ref name="anon">[http://www.strategypage.com/htmw/htiw/articles/20100123.aspx Anon, "Lost in the NIPRNET", January 2010, (Accessed on 19 April 2011, 6:01pm PST)]</ref>

Over the last decades,{{when|date=June 2013}} NIPRNet has grown faster than the U.S. Department of Defense can monitor. DoD spent $10 million in 2010 to map out the current state of the NIPRNet, in an effort to analyze its expansion, and identify unauthorized users, who are suspected to have quietly joined the network.<ref name="anon"/> The NIPRNet survey, which uses IPSonar software developed by [[Lumeta Corporation]], also looked for weakness in security caused by network configuration.<ref>[http://www.defensenews.com/article/20100118/DEFFEAT01/1180306/Mapping-Pentagon-s-Networks Mapping the Pentagon's Networks | Defense News]. defensenews.com (2014-02-24). Retrieved on 2014-04-12.</ref> The Department of Defense has made a major effort over the last few years,{{when|date=June 2013}} to improve [[network security]].<ref>[http://www.nextgov.com/nextgov/ng_20110324_2474.php "Pentagon seeks $3.2 billion for revised cyber budget" March, 2011 (Accessed on 19 April 2011)]</ref> The Pentagon announced it was requesting $2.3 billion in the 2012 budget to bolster network security within the Defense Department and to strengthen ties with its counterparts at the [[Department of Homeland Security]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

[[SIPRNet]] and NIPRNet are referred to [[colloquialism|colloquially]] as ''sipper-net'' and ''nipper-net'' (or simply ''sipper'' and ''nipper''), respectively.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}

